description: Vacuolar myopathy with autophagy, X-linked vacuolar myopathy with autophagy

value: Vacuolor myopathy with autophagy, X-linked vacuolor myopathy with autophagy
Mother has muscle signal changes on MRI
Thus presumed to be an X-linked myopathy
- DMD, LAMP2, myofibrillar myopathy panel performed testing for BAG3, crystalline B, desmin, DNAJB6, FLH1, LDB3, and myotilin. Non diagnostic.
- DMD testing revealed a hemizygous variant of unknown significance in the DMD gene.
- Fulgent Diagnostics identified a hemizygous VUS in the VMA21(XMEA); c.164G>T (p.Gly55Val). His mother also carried this variant.
8 yo male at time of testing. Ambulatory. Myopathy starting from 2 years of age with falls, elevated CK, and myopathic muscle biopsy. Clinical course is slowly progressive.
Exam showed proximal limb girdle pattern of weakness. Proximal upper and lower extremity weakness. Myopathy Congenital myopathy. Diminished muscle bulk / eps. scapular, Lordotic gait.

Muscle biopsy (2014) showed fiber size variability with prominent perimysial fibrous tissue; scattered myofibers with vacuoles staining dark blue with trichome and positive PAS staining; normal enzyme activity for phosphorylase, myoadenylase and phosphofructokinase.
Electron microscopy (2014) showed membrane bound vacuoles which contain glycogen and degenerated mitochondria; some of these vacuoles contain secondary lysosomes.
Mice during embryogenesis P1 and E16.5 animals exhibit a double-outlet right ventricle VSD. The surviving mice with this genotype are suspected to not have the VSD.

Animals were submitted for a full pathology screen of the heart and other tissues as a part of CPAM workup to confirm this phenotype and develop a more thorough characterization of this mutation. Submitted 3 homozygous males 4-6 months old and a littermate control for necropsy and histopathology.
Lungs, pyogranulomatous bronchopneumonia, chronic, multifocal, moderate to marked (suggestive of an aspiration pneumonia) Ear canal, suppurative otitis media, chronic, bilateral, severe

Findings in mutant mice are consistent in all 3 animals examined. Dilation of proximal esophagus was noted in 2/3 animals examined with minimal evidence of inflammation. Overall the etiology is unclear, but I suspect the cause of aspiration pneumonia was a result of dysphagia (Oropharyngeal dysphagia), possibly involving innervation and normal function of the esophagus.

NF1 patients do exhibit dysphagia and alterations in vocal quality, however, these changes are secondary to neurofibromas involving the innervation at these sites (esophagus and layrnx). There was no evidence of peripheral neurofibromas were noted in innervation to the esophagus or other organs or spinal plexiform ganglia or within the central nervous system.
Additional characterization of the cause of aspiration pneumonia is recommended, specifically functional assessment of swallowing to determine if dysphagia is present.
The etiology of bilateral middle ear infections seen in 2/3 animals with NF1 mutation, is uncertain.

Integrin 3 (ITGA3) is a multifunctional adhesion receptor that plays pivotal roles in orchestrating cellextracellular matrix interactions, thereby influencing cell adhesion, migration, and tissue organization.

The SERPINA1 gene encodes alpha-1-antitrypsin (AAT), also known as protease inhibitor (PI), a major plasma serine protease inhibitor. AAT complexes predominantly with elastase, but also with trypsin, chymotrypsin, thrombin, and bacterial proteases. The most important inhibitory action of AAT is that against neutrophil elastase (ELANE, or HLE; 130130), a protease that degrades elastin of the alveolar walls as well as other structural proteins of a variety of tissues (review by Cox, 2001).

content: Regarding the SERPINA1 gene: "This SERPINA1 result is consistent with this proband being at least a carrier for autosomal recessive SERPINA1-related alpha-
1-antitrypsin deficiency, but does not establish a molecular diagnosis as a second variant was not identified in this gene."

The region with the missense variant has many other VUSs. There are other pathogenic or likely pathogenic truncating variants including splice variants downstream (c.2261- c.2974) from this variant according to ClinVar.
One variant is in the Integrin alpha chain conserved family region in the Integrin alpha Ig-like domain 2 critical for cellcell and cellextracellular matrix adhesion as well as stability.

The second variant is a splice site variant acting on the amino acid 690 in the same region/domain. If functional this would cause loss of the downstream 3-integrin extracellular domains (remaining Ig-like modules, thigh, calf-1/2), as well as the transmembrane and cytoplasmic regions.

The SeprinA1 variant is well characterised and also reported as p.Glu264Val or the S allele. It is usually of clinical consequence only in the compound heterozygous state with another pathogenic allele that results in concentrations of alpha-1 antitrypsin (AAT) that fall below the protective threshold of 57 mg/dL (Stoller et al. 2014). The p.Glu288Val variant in a compound heterozygous state is not usually associated with a high risk for liver disease, though some individuals may be at an increased risk for lung disease (Turino et al. 1996). Individuals who are homozygous for the p.Glu288Val variant do not appear to be at an increased risk for clinical disease and often do not show any clinical symptoms (Ferrarotti et al. 2012). Curiel et al. (1989) demonstrated that the p.Glu288Val variant results in intracellular degradation of AAT protein prior to secretion.

attachments.name: First patient with ILNEB syndrome due to pathogenic variants in ITGA3 surviving to adulthood
attachments.comments: Interstitial Lung disease, Nephrotic syndrome and Epidermolysis Bullosa, also referred to as ILNEB syndrome is an extremely rare autosomal recessive condition, caused by pathogenic variants in ITGA3. 11 patients have previously been diagnosed with ILNEB syndrome of whom 7 died in infancy or early childhood. We report the only patient with ILNEB syndrome who survived past adolescence, partly due to a double lung transplant.

attachments.name: Genomic and clinical characterization of adult CVID patients: results from a single-centre turkish cohort
attachments.comments: Common Variable Immunodeficiency (CVID) is the most frequently encountered symptomatic primary immunodeficiency in clinical practice, presenting with heterogeneous clinical and genetic features. While traditionally considered polygenic, recent advances in genomic technologies have revealed monogenic causes in a significant subset of patients. Paper includes a finding of a homozygous ITGA3 insertion region variant that suggested a mild form of ILNED syndrome.

attachments.name: Nephrotic syndrome, skin involvement, and chronic lung disease
attachments.comments: WES result showed a homozygous mutation (c.3061C>T) causing a premature stop codon (p.Arg1021*) in the ITGA3 gene and the patient was diagnosed with ILNEB (interstitial lung disease, nephrotic syndrome, and epidermolysis bullosa) syndrome.Tarur et al. detected a homozygous splice site ITGA3 mutation in a patient with skin findings at the age of 2, who was diagnosed with nephrotic syndrome at the age of 4, and had an insidious onset of breathlessness at the age of 9 years. Liu et al. recently reported a compound heterozygous ITGA3 mutation in a patient who had skin findings shortly after birth, had recurrent respiratory tract infection at the age of 2, and was diagnosed with nephrotic syndrome at the age of 8 years

attachments.name: Integrins: An Overview of Structural and Functional Aspects
Heterozygous SERPINA1 Defects and Their Impact on Clinical Manifestations of Patients with Predominantly Antibody Deficiencies
attachments.comments: Ten CVID patients carried heterozygous pathogenic SERPINA1 defects with normal alpha-1 antitrypsin levels. Interestingly, the presence of the Z allele (rs28929474), which was found in three patients, was significantly associated with liver disease; hepatic complications were also observed in patients carrying the p.Leu23Gln (rs1379209512) and the p.Phe76del (rs775982338) alleles. Conversely, no correlation of SERPINA1 defective variants with respiratory complications was observed, although patients with pathogenic variants exhibit a reduced probability of developing autoimmune diseases.

attachments.name: A novel ITGA3 homozygous splice mutation in an ILNEB syndrome child with slow progression
attachments.comments: ILNEB (interstitial lung disease, nephrotic syndrome, epidermolysis bullosa) syndrome is caused by ITGA3 mutations. Demises usually happened at infancy. This study reports a complete ILNEB syndrome child with slow disease progression.
